<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Dow Jones's New Service
   Delivers Reports Via Fax
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   DJ
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   PRINCETON, N.J. -- Dow Jones Information Services, an
operating group of Dow Jones &amp; Co., introduced "Facts
Delivered," an information service that quickly delivers
detailed reports on thousands of public companies via
facsimile machine or electronic mail.
   The report will include the latest news about a company,
its current stock price, a detailed profile, financial data
from the company's income statement and balance sheet,
earnings estimates, its performance as compared with its
industry group, a summary of its recent insider transactions
and a list of research reports from investment analysts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "`Facts Delivered' is designed to provide business people
a comprehensive overview of a company with a single phone
call," said Richard J. Levine, vice president and editorial
director of the Information Services Group.
   Through an agreement with MCI Mail, customers receive the
report within hours of their request. The reports may be used
for competitive analyses as well as marketing and sales and
investment purposes.
   The reports are available for $70. The service hours are
Monday through Friday 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Eastern time.
   Dow Jones publishes The Wall Street Journal, Barron's, Dow
Jones News/Retrieval, five domestic and international
newswires -- including Dow Jones News Service -- and the
Ottaway group of community newspapers. The company also owns
Telerate Inc., a supplier of real-time financial information.
</TEXT>
