<HL>
   Eastern Indicted
   Over Failures
   In Maintenance
   ----
   By Amy Dockser Marcus and Bridget O'Brian
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   CTA LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   A federal grand jury in New York indicted Eastern Airlines
and nine current and former management employees on charges
of failing to perform mandatory maintenance on Eastern
aircraft and falsifying related records.
   In announcing the indictment, U.S. District Attorney
Andrew J. Maloney alleged that the scheme was directed from
Eastern's Miami headquarters and arose as the result of
pressure by upper management to avoid costly flight delays
and cancellations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   According to the indictment, some employees allegedly
engaged in "pencil whipping," or signing off on work that
wasn't performed, at Eastern's maintenance bases at John F.
Kennedy International Airport and La Guardia Airport in New
York and Hartsfield International Airport in Atlanta. Eastern
last year paid a $1.9 million civil penalty related to
similar charges after an investigation by the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   The 60-count indictment is unprecedented in commercial
aviation, and Mr. Maloney said at a news conference that he
sees the case as an example to the entire airline industry.
"If this is occurring at other airlines, they can expect a
lot of trouble," he said.
   In a statement released from its Miami headquarters,
Eastern reiterated that it has been extensively examined in
the past on such matters and has taken action to correct the
alleged abuses. "There is no question that Eastern is safe,"
the statement said.
   Eastern said Tuesday that plea bargain talks with
prosecutors had collapsed because it wouldn't accept a
broad-based conspiracy charge. Eastern said it had been
prepared to plead guilty to some charges of falsifying
records.
   The indictment alleges that in Atlanta, Eastern personnel
installed defective or untested electronic parts, including
cockpit instruments and other critical navigation equipment.
At all three airports, the indictment says, maintenance
personnel failed to perform repairs that would have delayed
aircraft, and then doctored records to indicate the work had
been completed.
   The defendants are also charged with conspiracy, wire
fraud and obstructing justice for giving false testimony
about the alleged plan at a Federal Aviation Administration
hearing.
   Named as defendants along with Eastern are Edward Upton,
until January a vice president, maintenance and engineering,
in Miami; Thomas Lewis, maintenance director of Eastern's
northern region airports, in Montreal, Washington and Boston;
and seven other supervisors. Mr. Upton couldn't be reached
for comment, and Eastern declined to comment on Mr. Lewis's
behalf.
   A spokeswoman for Eastern said the seven employees still
with the airline have been reassigned to non-maintenance
positions. But Mr. Maloney asserted that "up to a few days
ago, half of the managers charged were still on the payroll
and involved in maintenance."
   The Eastern spokeswoman said that effective yesterday the
seven were put on paid administrative leave and that Eastern
will pay their legal bills "as long as we are confident of
their innocence."
   If convicted on all counts, Eastern faces a maximum fine
of $30 million. Each individual defendant faces up to five
years in prison and fines of up to $250,000 on each count.
Mr. Maloney said that an indictment is expected to be filed
against another Eastern employee shortly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900726-0094
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900726-0094.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   Panhandle Eastern
   Cuts Payout 60%,
   Cites Cash Woes
   ----
   By Caleb Solomon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   PEL
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
EARNINGS (ERN)
PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Panhandle Eastern Corp., citing current and
potential cash problems, slashed its dividend 60% despite its
repeated insistence that the payout would remain intact.
   "Today's dividend action recognizes that financial and
operating improvements expected when we acquired {Texas
Eastern} are developing more slowly and less dramatically
than anticipated," Panhandle's new chairman, Philip
Burguieres, said in a letter to shareholders.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The natural gas pipeline company's debt soared after its
$3.22 billion acquisition of Texas Eastern Corp. in early
1989, with its debt-to-equity ratio moving above 70%. At the
time, many critics were skeptical that Panhandle would have
strong enough cash flow to maintain the dividend, with some
viewing the purchase price as too high. A spokesman said the
current debt ratio of about 65% is still well above the goal
of 50%.
   While layoffs or other cutbacks haven't been announced,
the company said it would consider them. The board "directed
management to examine carefully all areas in which cash can
be saved, including capital expenditures and operating
expenses," Mr. Burguieres wrote.
   The dividend cut, to 80 cents a share annually from $2 a
share, will save Panhandle about $105 million a year. Rumors
of the cut, which the company has denied ever since the Texas
Eastern acquisition and as recently as its annual meeting in
April, had been circulating on Wall Street for several weeks.
Panhandle's stock ended yesterday at $17.875, down 75 cents
in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Panhandle's difficulties were reflected in the
second-quarter earnings it announced yesterday. The company
said its loss widened to $13.6 million, or 15 cents a share,
from $5 million, or nine cents a share, a year earlier, which
included an $11.1 million one-time gain. Revenue declined
6.7% to $494 million from $529.4 million.
   Among the problems cited, the company said its cleanup of
polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, at Texas Eastern pipeline
stations would exceed its earlier $400 million estimate. "We
don't know how much higher" it will be, the spokesman said.
   Unexpectedly low oil and natural gas prices in the first
half hurt pipeline volumes, particularly in the Northeast and
New England, because many customers switched to industrial
fuel oil from natural gas.
   "Competitive pressures may become even more severe over
the short term," Mr. Burguieres said. The spokesman explained
that certain Panhandle pipeline rates to the Northeast will
go up in December, which could further hurt volume.
   Also, a number of expansion projects have been delayed or
curbed, reducing expected gas volume for the company.
   Panhandle said court rulings on regulatory matters could
force refunds that would strain cash holdings in the short
run, although the company said ultimately it will reap
positive cash in these cases. Panhandle said it may have an
unexpected $100 million tax liability because of Internal
Revenue Service interpretations affecting the sale of some
Texas Eastern assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900726-0093
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900726-0093.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Deficit-Reduction Agreement Appears
   Unlikely Before Congress Starts Recess
   ----
   By Jeffrey H. Birnbaum and David Wessel
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Budget negotiators appear unlikely to meet
their goal of reaching a deficit-reduction agreement before
Congress begins its August recess.
   Frustrated with the progress, President Bush in private
meetings raised the possibility of asking Congress to delay
its vacation. But leaders in Congress have asked him not to
take that action, and instead may convene summit talks during
the break.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The budget summit negotiators had hoped to reach an
agreement before the Aug. 3 beginning of the recess. But
congressional and administration officials now say that is
extremely unlikely. "It would take a miracle," said Chairman
Leon Panetta (D., Calif.) of the House Budget Committee.
   Congressional leaders advised the president not to take
the dramatic step of asking Congress to stay at work because
it would probably antagonize lawmakers more than foster
compromise. Instead, they discussed the possibility of having
the administration and congressional leaders continue talking
while Congress is away.
   The betting on Capitol Hill is that Congress will begin
its month-long vacation on time. Budget Director Richard
Darman declined to comment, but another White House official
said the president was "very serious" about his suggestion of
keeping Congress in session.
   House Minority Leader Robert Michel of Illinois quoted Mr.
Bush as asking, "Does it help any if I say you ought to stay
here if you don't get this agreement?" Mr. Michel also quoted
the president saying: "I want to make progress, I want to get
something going."
   "We told him the August thing is sacrosanct. He
understands that," Mr. Michel said. He also noted that it
might not make sense to keep the whole Congress in session
before an agreement is reached among the leaders.
   "It could be that we are hung up on three or four major
clumps of disagreement . . . and that we've got to have the
summit come back during August to try to get it completed,"
House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt (D., Mo.) said after
meeting with the president.
   Early in the day, Rep. Gephardt and White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater confirmed that administration and
congressional negotiators this week hope to trade
deficit-reduction packages aimed at paring the fiscal 1991
deficit by $50 billion. Mr. Fitzwater said the two sides
planned to introduce their proposals simultaneously, but
Democrats said they hadn't agreed to that.
   Staffers later were saying that such an exchange might not
occur soon, partly because Democrats and, to a lesser extent
Republicans, are having trouble reaching agreement among
themselves. If proposals are made soon, participants in the
talks said they are more likely to be refinements of opening
bargaining positions than major moves toward compromise.
   Meanwhile, the House Ways and Means Committee voted to
extend the federal borrowing limit. Congress will need to
raise the borrowing limit before it goes on recess. The panel
approved two versions of the debt-ceiling bill. One would
extend the limit until Oct. 15, and the other would extend
the ceiling through fiscal 1991. The short-term extension is
the more likely outcome, raising the limit to $3.195 trillion
from $3.122 trillion.
   The committee also voted, at the urging of Rep. Byron
Dorgan (D., N.D.), to ask the House Rules Committee to permit
a vote on the House floor to remove the Social Security Trust
Fund from the calculations that go into the Gramm-Rudman
deficit-reduction law. That amendment would be placed on the
long-term extension.
   Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski (D., Ill.) said he
hoped any amendments that are added to the legislation be
attached to the long-term extension and that the short-term
extension be passed amendment free.
   ---
   Michel McQueen contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
