<HL>
   Newsprint Use in U.S.
   Increased 3.1% in June
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The American Newspaper Publishers
Association estimated newsprint consumption by all U.S. users
at 1,013,331 metric tons in June, up 3.1% from a year
earlier.
   For the first half, the industry group estimated that
consumption rose 1.3% to 6,078,222 metric tons. A metric ton
is equal to about 2,204.62 pounds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The association said U.S. daily newspapers used 741,120
metric tons of newsprint in June, little changed from 740,484
tons a year earlier. Daily newspapers' consumption in the
first half rose less than 1% to 4,531,039 metric tons from
4,504,677 tons.
   Newsprint inventories of newspapers in the association's
statistical sample averaged a 43-day supply in June,
unchanged from a year earlier. The association said stocks of
North American mills were down 24%.
   The association said Canadian newsprint mills operated at
95% of rated capacity in June and in the first half, and U.S.
mills operated at 96.2% in June and 96.6% in the half.
</TEXT>
