900726-0029.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Panel Clears Bill to Donate
   Properties to Aid Homeless
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
approved legislation allowing the donation of surplus federal
property to non-profit groups working with homeless people.
   Currently, the government grants limited-term leases to
such qualified groups, an arrangement that public-interest
organizations have argued prohibits them from making
long-range plans.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Housing Secretary Anna Kondratas said the
administration welcomed the measure and would use its
regulatory authority to start deeding properties even before
final passage of the measure, which the committee approved by
voice vote.
   Deeding the property to groups dealing with the homeless
will make "a significant difference" in the program because
the lease arrangement currently thwarts those groups from
securing the financing needed to improve the facilities, said
Wendy Adler, of the National Governors' Association.
   The McKinney Homeless Assistance Act of 1987 is the
primary federal vehicle for aiding the homeless. But critics
have charged that one of its major programs, the
surplus-property program, has been less effective than it
could be because of government inefficiency and insufficient
information on available properties.
   "There is still no comprehensive federal guidance on how
to obtain federal vacant properties," John Ols, the director
of housing and community development issues of the General
Accounting Office, said last week in testmony before the
committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900726-0028
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900726-0028.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Ducommun Inc.:
   Firm Reports Sharp Increase
   In 2nd-Quarter Net Income
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   DCO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ducommun Inc., Los Angeles, posted a sharp increase in
second-quarter net income to $620,000, or 19 cents a share,
from $77,000, or two cents a share, a year ago. The company
said it expects full-year 1990 results to exceed those of
last year.
   Latest second-quarter net income included a tax credit of
$258,000, or 8 cents a share. Sales of the maker of aerospace
components and assemblies climbed 11%, to $19.7 million, from
$17.8 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We continue to expect sales and net income for the full
year to exceed 1989 results," said Norman A. Barkeley,
chairman, president and chief executive officer. "Our
commercial aerospace business is strong, and additional
reductions in overhead are being put into effect." In 1989,
Ducommun had net income of $602,000, or 18 cents a share, on
sales of $68.6 million.
   For the first six months of 1990, the company's net income
more than doubled to $896,000, or 27 cents a share, from
$437,000, or 13 cents a share, a year earlier. Net income for
the year-earlier period included a $456,000 loss from
discontinued operations. Revenue rose 10%, to $37.9 million,
from $34.3 million.
</TEXT>
