<HL>
   Business Brief -- Farley Inc.:
   Assets of a Unit Are Sold
   To Group for $135.5 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
07/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   X.FRY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Farley Inc., the cash-strapped holding company controlled
by investor William Farley, said it sold the assets of its
aluminum die-casting operation to an investor group for
$135.5 million in cash, notes and junk securities.
   Farley Inc. said in Chicago that the investor group, led
by closely held ICM Industries Inc., paid $88 million in cash
for the Doehler-Jarvis unit. It also issued Farley a $25
million subordinated note, which pays interest in like
securities for the first two years, and $15 million of other
so-called payment-in-kind debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   An additional $7.5 million cash payment "was deferred,"
Farley said in a news release. Officials weren't immediately
available for elaboration.
   Under the sale, Farley Inc. received an equity interest --
whose size wasn't disclosed -- in the partnership that bought
the unit. Farley retains on its books "certain liabilities"
of Doehler-Jarvis totaling $100 million.
</TEXT>
